This angel is 19 months old tomorrow 🥲 Kids really do start showing us who they are and what they love by now, so here are the two most remarkable things about Jude so far. 1) He’s a sports nut. Basketball is his favorite, he can sink shots from across the living room. He practices shooting over and over again. He can also dribble his little soccer ball down long hallways, and throw a full sized football. It blows our minds! 2) He is so, so loving. It started with giving long, slow kisses on the mouth to all of his stuffed animals😂 Then he started saying hi to every stranger and animal, usually high fiving them (from very far away) and blowing them kisses. Now, when he sees any creature that is sad, be they human or animal, real or invented, he tries to kiss and hug them to make them feel better. May we nurture the garden of his tender little heart! 🌱 
Obsessed with hims forever and ever. #19onthe19th

La langue de l’amour is calling you bébé! The 💕BEST💕way to learn a language is by practicing frequently while getting instantaneous, high-quality feedback. That feedback is what we are most often missing when we’re learning a language online. So! I have a brand new French offering pour vous: This is a drop-in conversation class hosted and lead by moi. Come once or come every week, come whenever you can! All levels welcome! I wanted to offer a low-pressure, supportive environment where you all you have to do is show up ready to practice your French. I will always have conversation starters and we will tackle all of your questions as they arise. We will always focus heavily on pronunciation. 
💘Swipe through for details and please email 

f r e n c h w i t h M A F @ g m a i l . c o m 

to sign up, and drop your  questions in the comments! So… who will be there this Saturday?!? 🙋🏼‍♀️💕

Happy Mother’s Day! I hope I never forget how I felt after Jude was born. I thought “Oh, wow, I finally feel like an adult! Huh!” I thought “Oh, wow, I feel like myself again!” (Jude’s placenta and I did *not* get along and she totes tried to kill me with high blood pressure but guess I got the last laugh ‘cause I ate her in capsule form! JK but I should have) But most of all, I could NOT believe what Jude and I had just gone through together (bonding, more like trauma bonding amiright?!?) I could NOT BELIEVE that allllll these mothers are just walking around out there like nothing had happened, when in fact they had voyaged deep into the liminal space between life and death to bring their babies here. It was giving River Styx, it was giving underworld, it was giving Hades, babes. But the moms know. They are forever changed. And maybe it’s our cultural irreverence to this reality that turns moms “crazy.” We desperately need to treat parents, espeeeeecially anyone who identifies as a mother, mothers of all genders, with more reverence in America. DESPERATELY. Like if we are all not bringing Beyoncé in a crown on a bed of roses energy to this whole thing?!?!? We are doing it all wrong. Motherhood is the most profound and enriching undertaking of my life and even here in these crusty rusty dusty musty United States, I would not trade it. Phew anywayyyyssss here is an incredible photo by @brunagenovesephotography. I said maternity, but make it Slim Aarons? And she said BAM. Love to all the mamas!!! and most especially mine, @dieselfarina 🥰 I am your oldest and therefore best child shhh I’ll never tell! 👩‍👧
#mothersday #maternity

WHAT ARE YOU DOING SUNDAY NIGHT? Why, coming to see me in conversation with my BFF, @stmartinspress and @wmebooks author @karintanabe at @storiesbooksandcafe to discuss her seventh novel The Sunset Crowd, out this week, a seductive Gatsby-esque (according to the Washington Post in their glowing review, nbd) page-turner set in 1970s LA, of course!

Karin is my bestie and my shero. To name just one cool highlight among her many accomplishments, her novel set at our alma mater Vassar College, The Gilded Years, has been optioned to be a major motion picture starring Zendaya produced by Reese Witherspoon and Hello Sunshine! 

We are finally joining forces to talk all things LA, creativity, fabulous women, writing, and of course all of these things in relation to her latest ✨powerhouse✨novel The Sunset Crowd. If we’ve never met, this is the perfect chance to say hi, meet Karin, and grab your signed copy of the Sunset Crowd. If we’re already friends, well, you’re legally obligated to be there! Come join us for a book talk with drinks to follow across the street at Lowboy! We’ll be in our 70s attire, you can be too! 
☀️🌴🕺🏻✨🪩

In case you haven’t seen my many story updates and wondered why the heck I never post anything anymore, it’s because this summer my mom, @dieselfarina, has been in a fight for her very life. She was taken to the ER by ambulance after fainting so dramatically that she gave herself a huge black eye. That started a now near 7-week journey of life in the hospital. She spent a terrifying week declining rapidly as they subjected to a grueling series of tests to diagnose her with heart problems we never had a clue about. She had a risky but, thank God, successful heart ablation, a temporary and permanent pacemaker placed, has overcome pneumonia, sepsis, and ARDS (probably brought on by a coughing fit so bad she thought she was drowning, immediately following her first extubation😣). She’s been airlifted from one hospital to another, been in and out of the ICU three times, been intubated and extubated twice, and has had 10 different hospital rooms. And now, in what we truly hope and pray will be the beginning of the last chapter of her ordeal, she has a brand new tracheostomy that took two surgeries and three days to place because of her surprisingly long airway (she is 5’11”, after all). This will help her lungs, compromised from a phrenic nerve injury and unilateral diaphragm paralysis, get the support they need to recover from all of this deconditioning. My God! Many, if not all, of her current problems are the result of chest radiation for Hodgkins back in 1991. The scorched earth cure back then saved her life, but at the enormous cost she’s paying now. STILL, she has fought through incredible suffering and is winning this fight. Her doctors and nurses are nothing short of miracle workers. They are nearly as invested in her recovery as we are at this point. We’re staying positive and keeping the faith that this tough cookie will make a full recovery, back to even better health than before. Thank you all for following along and offering so much support. ❤️🙏
#lateeffectsofcancertreatment #hodgkinslymphomasurvivor #lateeffectsofradiation #lateeffectsradiation

My mom. My person. Me. My heart. A sparkling, childlike, tremendously FUN, tremendously faithful, guileless person without one single ounce of cynicism or self-importance. I just looked at her Google calendar—it was nothing but everyone else’s birthdays, anniversaries, reminders to do things for people. Trips to see family and events she was planning. This is my mom. The mommiest mom. When I finally went to school for the first time in 1st grade, I cried on my teacher Mrs. Balog’s lap all day for weeks. I wanted nothing but to be with her. I can feel myself running to her in the sunshine outside of school getting scooped up in a huge squishy Chanel No.5-scented hug. When she got sick the first time when I was 10, a mortal dread entered my body that has never left me. Every night and every morning my first thoughts are “is mom okay?” Not just recently, but since I was 10.  It’s just always been this way. I would often text her at night before bed to say I love you just to ease my worry a bit, feel close to her. I would go to my dad’s house as a kid and write “I miss mom so so so [filling literal pages with the word so] much,” over and over. When she would work late nights at the Orioles games, I would leave multi-page letters for when she got home, begging her to wake me up so we could have some special time together. Often she would, and she’d make me warm maple milk and we’d go look at the stars and talk. She’d leave me notes too, for whenever she was gone. She’d put them in my award-winning school lunches. Constant reminders of her devotion. If she was thinking something nice about you, you’d get an email or a text. She’d send care packages and “fish presents,” “just for the halibut!” In her purse I just found Dunkin’ Donut gift cards with a note saying “thank you for your service!” She liked to give them to firemen she encountered. She always chose others over herself, always. Without hesitation we were her world. We had grand plans of traveling the world and living together again. We talked about home schooling Jude together. We had so many projects and dreams. Mom you were robbed of your ease-filled golden years. We are utterly bereft.

This little Padam Padam act was one of her favorite things to do together. I actually forgot we ever recorded this and I’m so happy to have it. This is directed by mommy and captures us pretty well. I know I wouldn’t have liked it then because I didn’t pronounce my “du” perfectly once and I hated my singing. But watching it now that feels so silly. It’s us, so it’s perfect. Voilà our band, Les Pommes de Paris. 🍏💔🍎
Please share with anyone who knew my mama. Wake time 5-7pm.

Never in a million years did I think this would be your last birthday. Your mom is 95. Your dad smoked forever and still passed peacefully at home in his sleep in his 80s. There must be some reason God needed you home but my feeble mortal mind probably won’t understand until it’s my turn. In the meantime, everyone, throw that surprise party. Tell them you love them. Take fewer pictures of your dumb boyfriend and more of your parents. Ask them everything. Tell them everything. Go on trips with them. Call them more. Answer their emails. And if they feel kind of crappy, don’t tell them to drink water and exercise. Get their hearts checked by someone good. 
I’ll miss you every day as long as I live, my best perfect mom. Happy birthday in heaven.

This is the face we’ll both make when we see each other again. Flying away from mom’s going home ceremony. And what a ceremony it was. The choir was only children she had taught, and they wiped away tears from their precious little faces. The readings were done by my sister and sister-in-law, the pallbearers were Anthony and my brother and my mom’s brother and her cousin and our childhood friends. The priest was mom’s very good friend of 20 years, who was with us the last night in the hospital. He wiped away tears through the most beautiful homily I’ve ever heard—a paean to mom. He really, really knew her spirit. He talked about how she taught HIM about faith and humility, not the other way around. But never didactically. Never boastfully. “She witnessed it,” he said, she lived it. Blessed are the meek, the pure of heart.

What would I do without all of you who are surrounding me with love right now? The first glimmers of seeing anything beautiful in such a great loss have come for me in the love and tenderness I feel from so many people. This is an hour after I gazed on my mom’s beautiful face and lay my hands on her piano hands for the very last time. @markycb held me as I sobbed by her casket. @karintanabe and @anthonyguerino took me to eat foie gras and drink champagne in her honor, to help me with my eulogy, and to task themselves entirely with somehow churning out a couple hundred perfectly crafted funeral mass programs before 10 a.m. the following day. Anthony, you’re the definition of a husband. Karin and Marcus, you’re the definition of best friends. Through thick and thin. So many more appreciation posts to come. Love you

I wish I could hop back into my old life so, so much. But there’s just no avoiding that life without my mom will never be the same. I’ll be ok, and I’ll be a better, softer, more compassionate version of myself someday. But the transition might not be cute. This is a brutal process. I’m the world’s most raggedy little pupa in my crusty little cocoon. Becoming a mother myself was the only thing remotely as transformative that’s ever happened to me. 
Just like becoming a mom, losing my mom will change every cell in my body. There’s no muddling through, there’s no back to normal life. Our culture is kind of sick to expect that of us. And I’m lucky to have had such a mom to leave such a lack. There’s only a new life that awaits on the other side of this chasm. 
Rilke called it “The strangeness that has entered us.” That phrase echoes in my mind. He says: “Because we are alone with the strangeness that has entered us; because all that we trusted and were used to has been taken away from us for a moment; because we are in the middle of a transformation where we cannot be stable. That is why the sorrows also pass: the New Thing in us, that has come into us, has gone into our heart, into its innermost chamber, and is already no longer there-- it is already in our blood. And we don't learn what it was....We can't say who is come, we may never know, but many indications show that the Future has entered us in this way, to transform inside of us, long before it happens.” 
Here’s to that future, mom. With you as my saint and my guiding light. I share this to connect with anyone who grieves today, and because maybe something about her will inspire you to love and live as fearlessly as she did. With love from the crusty strangeness.

Christmas without my mommy. “Mom mommy mommy mommy MOM!” I find myself whispering or even crying it out. Jude cries out for me this way. I hear his voice in my head as I say the words, mom mommy mommy mommy MOM. He wants his mommy just as viscerally as I want mine. The other night I woke up crying out for her at one a.m., and not three minutes later he woke up crying out for me. I put him on my chest to fall back asleep and there we stayed for two hours, comforting each other. I think often of a shower I took two days before she left, falling on the bathtub floor screaming begging demanding MY MOMMY?!? Why aren’t you saving her, God? Why does she look so sick, God? Why do these bad things keep happening to her, God? I was so sure he’d let his devoted servant live. (I don’t think it works this way but big ups to bargaining.) It’s impossible to turn away from sadness this Christmas when Bethlehem, birthplace of the baby who started it all, sits in rubble. Why do bad things happen to all those good people? I don’t know. But I am trying to choose faith anyway because my mom did. Because Gazans do. It ain’t easy and I’m failing most days, tbh. But I’ll keep trying because this is a practice. Mom’s faith was a series of small decisions she made every day. Faith in each other, in goodness, in kindness, in our shared commitment to the healing all this suffering eventually brings. In the meantime, love the ones you got. Happy Sad Holidays to all.
